  <xi:include href="slidesinfo.ptx"/>
  <slideshow>
    <title>Polynomial Fitting</title>
    <subtitle>(Section 2.3)</subtitle>
    <slide>
      <title>Investigate!</title>
      
      
        <p permid="cio">
        A standard <m>8 \times 8</m> chessboard contains 64 squares.
        Actually, this is just the number of unit squares.
        How many squares of all sizes are there on a chessboard?
        Start with smaller boards:
        <m>1\times 1</m>, <m>2 \times 2</m>, <m>3\times 3</m>, etc.
        Find a formula for the total number of squares in an <m>n\times n</m> board.
      </p>
    
    </slide>
    <slide>
      <title><m>\Delta^k</m>-constant Sequences</title>
      <p>
        Consider the sequence
        <me>
          1, 5, 14, 30, 55,\ldots
        </me>
      </p>
      <p pause="yes">
        We can compute the <term>sequence of differences</term>:
        <me>
          4, 9, 16, 25\ldots
        </me>
        and then the <term>second differences</term> (differences of differences):
        <me>
          5, 7, 9,\ldots
        </me>
      </p>
      <p pause="yes">
        Eventually some <m>k</m>-th level of differences <em>might</em> be constant (as they are here at the 3rd differences).  Let's call such a sequence a <term><m>\Delta^k</m>-constant sequence</term>.
      </p>
    </slide>
    <slide>
      <example source-number="2.3.1">
        <statement>
          <p permid="DFE">
          Which of the following sequences are
          <m>\Delta^k</m>-constant for some value of <m>k</m>?

          <ol permid="gin"><li permid="swF"><m>2, 3, 7, 14, 24, 37,\ldots</m>.</li>
          <li permid="YDO"><m>1, 8, 27, 64, 125, 216, \ldots</m>.</li>
          <li permid="EKX"><m>1,2,4,8,16,32,64,\ldots</m>.</li></ol>
        </p>
        </statement>
      </example>
    </slide>
    <slide>

        <title>Finite Differences</title>
        <p permid="tgz">
        The closed formula for a sequence will be a degree <m>k</m> polynomial if and only if the sequence is <m>\Delta^k</m>-constant (i.e., the <m>k</m>th sequence of differences is constant).
      </p>
      <p pause="yes">
        When we know that a sequence can be <q>fit</q> to a polynomial of a particular degree, we can find the coefficients using the initial terms of the sequence.
      </p>
    </slide>
    <slide>
      <example source-number="2.3.2">
        <statement>
          <p permid="jMN">
          Find a formula for the sequence <m>3, 7, 14, 24,\ldots</m>.
          Assume <m>a_1 = 3</m>.
        </p>
        </statement>
      </example>
    </slide>
    <slide>
      <example source-number="2.3.3">
        <statement>
          <p permid="PTW">
          Find a closed formula for the number of squares on an <m>n \times n</m> chessboard.
        </p>
        </statement>
      </example>
    </slide>
    <slide>
      <example source-number="2.3.4">
        <statement>
          <p permid="wbf">
          Determine whether the following sequences can be described by a polynomial,
          and if so, of what degree.

          <ol permid="Mpw"><li permid="dnH"><m>1, 2, 4, 8, 16, \ldots</m></li>
          <li permid="JuQ"><m>0, 7, 50, 183, 484, 1055, \ldots</m></li>
          <li permid="pBZ"><m>1,1,2,3,5,8,13,\ldots</m></li></ol>
        </p>
        </statement>
      </example>
    </slide>
  </slideshow>
